04963nam a22008055i 9780520928985DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20002000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209289857 a10.1525/97805209289852doi  a(DE-B1597)520460  a(OCoLC)609850095  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML3508b.L48 2000 7aMUS0250002bisacsh04a781.652231 aLevin, Floyd, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aClassic Jazz :bA Personal View of the Music and the Musicians /cFloyd Levin. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (358 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tFOREWORD -- tPREFACE -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. KID ORY AND THE REVIVAL ERA -- t2. A PERSONAL VIEW OF THE MUSIC -- t3. A PERSONAL VIEW OF THE MUSICIANS -- t4. THE INFLUENCE OF NEW ORLEANS MUSICIANS ON CLASSIC JAZZ -- t5. THE GREAT LOUIS ARMSTRONG -- t6. JAZZ ON THE WEST COAST -- t7. UNSUNG HEROES -- t8. THE SEVEN-YEAR CHALLENGE TO COMPLETE THE LOUIS ARMSTRONG STATUE -- tEPILOGUE -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFloyd Levin, an award-winning jazz writer, has personally known many of the jazz greats who contributed to the music's colorful history. In this collection of his articles, published mostly in jazz magazines over a fifty-year period, Levin takes us into the nightclubs, the recording studios, the record companies, and, most compellingly, into the lives of the musicians who made the great moments of the traditional jazz and swing eras. Brilliantly weaving anecdotal material, primary research, and music analysis into every chapter, Classic Jazz: A Personal View of the Music and the Musicians is a gold mine of information on a rich segment of American popular music. This collection of articles begins with Levin's first published piece and includes several new articles that were inspired by his work on this compilation. The articles are organized thematically, beginning with a piece on Kid Ory's early recordings and ending with a newly written article about the campaign to put up a monument to Louis Armstrong in New Orleans. Along the way, Levin gives in-depth profiles of many well-known jazz legends, such as Jelly Roll Morton, Duke Ellington, and Louis Armstrong, and many lesser-known figures who contributed greatly to the development of jazz. Extensively illustrated with previously unpublished photographs from Levin's personal collection, this wonderfully readable and extremely personal book is full of information that is not available elsewhere. Classic Jazz: A Personal View of the Music and the Musicians will be celebrated by jazz scholars and fans everywhere for the overview it provides of the music's evolution, and for the love of jazz it inspires on every page.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aJazz musiciansxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aJazz musicianszUnited States. 0aJazzxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Jazz.2bisacsh  aamerican music.  aclassical jazz.  aclassical music.  acompilation.  aessay collection.  ajazz club.  ajazz magazine.  ajazz music.  ajazz musician.  ajazz musicians.  alouis armstrong.  amagazines.  amusic history.  amusic industry.  amusical genres.  amusicians.  anightclub.  apopular culture.  apopular music.  arecord companies.  arecording studio.  aswing music.  awestern music.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092898540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520928985423Coveruhttps://